<dl id="n08091i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08091i">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08091i"> 91(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pensamiento / (time to think) <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08091i"><li>FW 443.15 </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/lexqA.htm#n08091i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/qA/l39qA.htm#n08091i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08091i">MS VI.F.6-6</ms> </li><li>JJA not reproduced <a name="qAd10dash" href="../../ff/fdra/qda.htm#qAd10dash">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/qA/qAd10.htm#n08091i">Draft: III&sect;2A.10</a>'</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Let me quote here also a quaint passage (not to be taken too seriously) from Howell (<cite>New English Grammar</cite>, 1662, p.40): &lsquo;The Spanish abound and delight in words of many syllables and where the English expresseth himself in one syllable, he doth in 5 or 6, as thoughts pensamientos, fray levantamiento &amp;c, which is held a part of wisdom, for while they speak they take time to consider of the matter.&rsquo; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 137 [Nomenclature]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
